@startuml
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
autonumber "<b>[0]"

actor "sidetree-core-go" as User1
participant "Instance 1\nOperation Queue" as Instance1_OQ
database "orb.operation\ndatabase" as DB { }
rectangle "op-queue\nDB" as OPQueue_DB
participant "Instance 2\nOperation Queue" as Instance2_OQ


User1 ->> Instance1_OQ : Add(op1)
activate Instance1_OQ
    Instance1_OQ ->> DB : Publish(op1)
    activate DB 
        return ok  
    deactivate DB
    
return ok 

deactivate Instance1_OQ



User1 ->> Instance2_OQ : Add(op2)
activate Instance2_OQ
    Instance2_OQ ->> DB : Publish(op2)
    activate DB 
        return ok  
    deactivate DB
    
return ok 


db --> Instance1_OQ : op2
activate Instance1_OQ
   db <- - Instance1_OQ :ok
   
   
     instance1_oq->OPQUEUE_db:Put(op2,handler1ID,expiry)\n<color:red><size=8>(visibility timeout)</size></color>\nop queue stores operation in <i>Inflight</I> state \nto prevent other instances from processing this message.\nThe visibility_timeout value specifies how long to wait before making the item visible again if not acknowledged by handler.
     
      note right of user1 #lightyellow:<u>Note:</u>\nsidtree core go has two handlers:\nhandler1 for handling operations on sidetree blockchain,\nhandling means creating batches and writing them into batch files store;\ni.e., adding new blocks/transactions onto chain; or updating existing ones based upon changes made since last update cycle ran successfully without errors occurring during execution time period specified above). Handler processes messages asynchronously using goroutines so there may be delays between receiving request/response pairs due network latency issues etc.. Also keep mind about potential race conditions where multiple requests arrive simultaneously causing conflicts over shared resources like memory allocation/deallocation routines used throughout entire application stack including third party libraries imported along way too! So always test thoroughly under various scenarios involving high load situations especially those related concurrency control mechanisms employed here such locks semaphores mutexes atomic variables channels queues pools buffers caches threads executors schedulers timers alarms signals interrupts exceptions faults crashes hangs deadlocks livelocks starvation bottlenecks contention thrashing fragmentation garbage collection heap overflow stack exhaustion resource leaks file descriptor limits socket connections open ports firewall rules dns resolution timeouts retries backoff strategies circuit breakers bulkheads fallbacks graceful degradation failover clustering replication sharding partitioning scaling up/down out/in auto-healing self-repair monitoring alerting logging tracing debugging profiling benchmarking optimization tuning refactoring rewriting redesign rearchitect migration upgrade downgrade rollback hotfix patch release deployment configuration management infrastructure provisioning orchestration automation testing validation verification certification compliance auditing security privacy governance risk assessme